    "narrative": "Today\u2019s outlook for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on exploiting high-ceiling matchups against soft pitching rotations, with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (75.89) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.17) emerging as our elite starts. **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive 14% park boost and a favorable matchup against Tyler Glasnow, but his true value lies in the \"Slow SP Delivery\" bonus, which increases our stolen base probability\u2014a critical factor for our scarcity-driven strategy. Similarly, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** takes advantage of a 15% SP skill boost against Michael Wacha. While **Austin Riley** (71.42) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (72.72) also land in the 70s, **Tyler Soderstrom** specifically benefits from the same park/SP favorable combination as **Max Muncy**, providing a high-floor offensive anchor in the middle of our lineup.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Alex Freeland**, who posted a 58.63 score, nearly forcing his way into the starting nine. Ultimately, **Alex Freeland** was squeezed out by the batting order; the projection assumes an eighth or ninth spot, and the resulting negative order adjustment outweighed his park-driven efficiency. We are also keeping a close watch on **Corbin Carroll** (64.34); despite a 6% penalty for a neutral-to-negative platoon split against Eric Lauer, his xwOBA of 0.372 keeps him firmly in the lineup. Conversely, we are playing it safe with **James Wood** (52.25) and **Josh Naylor** (49.78) on the bench today, as both face elite arms in Logan Webb and Jacob deGrom, respectively, which suppresses their scoring potential below our \"Strong\" start threshold.\n\nWe remain at the mercy of \"Lineup Pending\" designations across the board, which introduces non-trivial risk regarding our assumed order-based bonuses. Specifically, **Luis Campusano** (42.06) sits at the very bottom of our active roster; if he slides lower than the assumed #8 spot, he risks falling below the efficiency floor entirely. We are banking on **Brice Turang** to maximize his 85% SB potential against Janson Junk, as his 65.19 score is heavily contingent on his position at #2. Ensure all active notifications are set, as any late-scratch lineup shifts could necessitate a rapid re-evaluation of the bench depth provided by **Jose Caballero**.",
